    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely. The South and West Side of Chicago have historically faced significant challenges, including higher rates of poverty and crime. Neighborhoods such as West Garfield Park and Humboldt Park have notable crime rates and may benefit from improved community resources such as new parks.\n\nOn the other hand, the North Side, particularly in areas like River North and Kenwood, generally has lower crime rates and stronger community stability. Investing in new parks here could enhance community life without as much risk of facing the same issues as seen in the South and West Side.\n\nHowever, it’s important to also consider pockets of middle-income suburbs on the Northwest Side, like Rogers Park or Rogers Park Extension, which may also need improvement but typically have lower crime rates compared to some South Side neighborhoods. Balancing these factors can help ensure the new park funds positively impact the most needed areas first, while maintaining overall safety and community stability.",
